During the last few years, computers have arrived in the high school. In 1983, Becker reported that 53% of all schools had one or more microcomputer, including 85% of the high schools and 42% of the elementary schools in this country. In just half a year, the number of secondary schools having five or more microcomputers actually doublcd.[l] In 1983, the typical secondary school owned five microcomputers which were used by approximately 80 students per week.[2] In 1986. Becker reported that over one-half of the secondary schools in the United States owned over 15 computers and a majority of the elementary school had five or more computers. He further stated that the number of computers in school quadrupled in two years, tripling the number of students using them and tbe number of teachers supervising students in their use.[3].